# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-opensearch-service
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is distributed and uses JSON documents stored in indices divided into shards, each of which may have replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] It supports full-text search, faceted search, real-time search, and multitenancy.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] The software is developed alongside Logstash, Kibana, and Beats as part of the Elastic Stack (formerly the ELK Stack).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Shay Banon created the precursor to Elasticsearch, called Compass, in 2004.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Developing a third version of Compass, he concluded that a full rewrite was necessary to build a scalable, distributed search solution using JSON over HTTP as a common interface.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] He released the first version of Elasticsearch in February 2010.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Elastic NV was founded in 2012 to provide commercial services and products around Elasticsearch and related software.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] In June 2014, the company raised $70 million in a Series C funding round led by New Enterprise Associates, with additional funding from Benchmark Capital and Index Ventures, bringing total funding to $104 million.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] In March 2015, the company changed its name from *Elasticsearch* to *Elastic* and, through the acquisition of Found, launched a managed cloud offering later known as Elastic Cloud.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] In November 2017, Elastic acquired the search startup Swiftype, whose technology became the basis for Elastic App Search and Elastic Site Search.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Elastic also formed partnerships with Google to offer Elastic Cloud on Google Cloud Platform and with Alibaba to offer Elasticsearch and Kibana on Alibaba Cloud.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] In June 2018, Elastic filed for an initial public offering with an estimated valuation of between $1.5 and $3 billion.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] On 5 October 2018, Elastic was listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] In January 2021, Elastic announced that starting with version 7.11, Elasticsearch and Kibana would be relicensed from Apache License 2.0 to a dual license under the Server Side Public License and the Elastic License, neither of which is recognised as an open-source license.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Elastic stated the change was a response to Amazon Web Services (AWS) offering Elasticsearch and Kibana as a service without what Elastic described as adequate collaboration.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Critics of the change noted that Elastic had previously promised never to alter the Apache 2.0 licensing of Elasticsearch, Kibana, Beats, and Logstash, and predicted the move would damage the ecosystem.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] AWS responded by announcing a fork of the projects to continue development under Apache License 2.0.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Other members of the Elasticsearch ecosystem, including Logz.io, CrateDB, and Aiven, also committed to supporting a fork.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Due to potential trademark conflicts with the name "Elasticsearch", AWS rebranded their fork as OpenSearch in April 2021.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] In August 2024, Elastic added the GNU Affero General Public License as a third licensing option for Elasticsearch starting with version 8.16.0.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] This made the software available under a free and open-source license once again alongside the two source-available options.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is built on Apache Lucene and exposes Lucene's capabilities through a JSON and Java API.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Documents are stored in indices, which are divided into primary shards; each shard may have zero or more replicas distributed across cluster nodes.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Routing and rebalancing are handled automatically.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Once an index has been created, the number of primary shards cannot be changed.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] The engine supports faceted search and percolation, a form of prospective search in which stored queries are matched against incoming documents rather than the reverse.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] A gateway module handles long-term index persistence, allowing an index to be recovered after a node failure.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Real-time GET requests make Elasticsearch usable as a NoSQL datastore, though it does not support distributed transactions.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] In May 2019, Elastic made the core security features of the Elastic Stack available without charge, including TLS for encrypted communications, file and native realm authentication, and role-based access control for cluster APIs and indices.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] The corresponding source code is available under the Elastic License.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch also offers SIEM and machine learning capabilities as part of its commercial offerings.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Official client libraries are maintained for Java, C# (.NET), PHP, Python, and Ruby, among others.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] Elasticsearch is developed alongside Logstash (a data collection and log-parsing engine), Kibana (an analytics and visualisation platform), and Beats (lightweight data shippers).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] The four products are designed for use together as the Elastic Stack.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/elasticsearch] The combination was previously known as the ELK Stack, an initialism for "Elasticsearch, Logstash, and Kibana".
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] In text retrieval, **full-text search** refers to a set of techniques for searching a single computer-stored document or a collection in a full-text database.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Full-text search is distinguished from searches based on metadata or on specific parts of documents, such as titles, abstracts, selected sections, or bibliographical references.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] In a full-text search, a search engine examines the words in stored documents to find matches for user queries.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Full-text-search techniques began to appear in the 1960s (for example, IBM STAIRS in 1969), and became common in online bibliographic databases during the 1990s.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Many websites and application programs, including word processors, implement full-text search functionality.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Some web search engines, such as the former AltaVista, indexed the full text of web pages, while others indexed only selected portions of pages.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] When dealing with a small number of documents, a full-text-search engine can scan the contents of each document directly for every query, a strategy known as "serial scanning." Some tools, such as grep, operate in this way.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] When the number of documents or queries is large, full-text search is typically divided into two tasks: indexing and searching.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] During indexing, the engine scans all documents and builds a list of search terms, often called an index, or more precisely, a concordance.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] During the search stage, queries are performed against the index rather than the original documents.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] The indexer records each term found in a document and may note its position within the text.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Common words, known as stop words (for instance, "the" or "and"), are omitted because they add little value to search results.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] The diagram at the right illustrates a search with low recall and low precision.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] In the diagram, red and green dots represent the total population of potential search results for a given query, with green dots indicating relevant results and red indicating irrelevant results.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Relevance is indicated by proximity to the center of the inner circle.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] The results actually returned by the search are highlighted on a light-blue background.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] In the example, only one relevant result of three possible relevant results was returned, giving a recall of ⅓ (33%).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] The precision is 1/4 (25%), since only one of the four results returned was relevant.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Due to the ambiguities of natural language, full-text-search systems typically include features such as filtering to increase precision and stemming to increase recall.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Controlled-vocabulary search can also help alleviate low-precision results by tagging documents to reduce ambiguity.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] There is generally a trade-off between precision and recall: increasing precision can reduce overall recall, while increasing recall may lower precision.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Full-text search can retrieve many documents that are not relevant to the intended query.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Such documents are called **false positives** (see Type I error).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] The retrieval of irrelevant documents is often caused by the inherent ambiguity of natural language.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] In the accompanying diagram, false positives are represented by irrelevant results (red dots) that were returned by the search (highlighted on a light-blue background).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] At a basic level, search engines return items that contain the exact phrase listed in the query.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Tools and methodologies exist to account for grammatical or typographical errors and to refine results; however, these techniques still typically require a close textual match.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Because there are often multiple ways to refer to an entity or concept, full-text search may fail to retrieve an item if the exact term is not used in the query.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Not to be confused with semantic search, synonyms can be retrieved by creating an index of related terms, such that when a variation of a word is searched, items containing any of the related terms may also be returned.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] The limitations of full-text searching have been addressed in two ways: by providing users with tools to express search questions more precisely, and by developing algorithms that improve retrieval precision.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] The following is a partial list of software products that support full-text indexing and search.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/full-text-search] Some of these are accompanied by documentation describing their architecture or algorithms, which may provide additional insight into how full-text search is implemented.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] The purpose of an inverted index is to allow fast full-text searches, at a cost of increased processing when a document is added to the database.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] The inverted file may be the database file itself, rather than its index.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] It is the most popular data structure used in document retrieval systems, used on a large scale for example in search engines.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] Additionally, several significant general-purpose mainframe-based database management systems have used inverted list architectures, including ADABAS, DATACOM/DB, and Model 204.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] There are two main variants of inverted indexes: A **record-level inverted index** (or **inverted file index** or just **inverted file**) contains a list of references to documents for each word.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] A **word-level inverted index** (or **full inverted index** or **inverted list**) additionally contains the positions of each word within a document.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] The latter form offers more functionality (like phrase searches), but needs more processing power and space to be created.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] The inverted index data structure is a central component of a typical search engine indexing algorithm.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] A goal of a search engine implementation is to optimize the speed of the query: find the documents where word X occurs.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] Once a forward index is developed, which stores lists of words per document, it is next inverted to develop an inverted index.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] Querying the forward index would require sequential iteration through each document and to each word to verify a matching document.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] The time, memory, and processing resources to perform such a query are not always technically realistic.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] Instead of listing the words per document in the forward index, the inverted index data structure is developed which lists the documents per word.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] With the inverted index created, the query can be resolved by jumping to the word ID (via random access) in the inverted index.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] In pre-computer times, concordances to important books were manually assembled.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] These were effectively inverted indexes with a small amount of accompanying commentary that required a tremendous amount of effort to produce.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] In bioinformatics, inverted indexes are very important in the sequence assembly of short fragments of sequenced DNA.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] One way to find the source of a fragment is to search for it against a reference DNA sequence.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] A small number of mismatches (due to differences between the sequenced DNA and reference DNA, or errors) can be accounted for by dividing the fragment into smaller fragments—at least one subfragment is likely to match the reference DNA sequence.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] The matching requires constructing an inverted index of all substrings of a certain length from the reference DNA sequence.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] Since the human DNA contains more than 3 billion base pairs, and we need to store a DNA substring for every index and a 32-bit integer for index itself, the storage requirement for such an inverted index would probably be in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/inverted-index] For historical reasons, inverted list compression and bitmap compression were developed as separate lines of research, and only later were recognized as solving essentially the same problem.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] In computer log management and intelligence, **log analysis** (or *system and network log analysis*) is an art and science seeking to make sense of computer-generated records (also called log or audit trail records).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] The process of creating such records is called data logging.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Logs are emitted by network devices, operating systems, applications and all manner of intelligent or programmable devices.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] A stream of messages in time sequence often comprises a log.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Logs may be directed to files and stored on disk or directed as a network stream to a log collector.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Log messages must usually be interpreted concerning the internal state of its source (e.g., application) and announce security-relevant or operations-relevant events (e.g., a user login, or a systems error).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Logs are often created by software developers to aid in the debugging of the operation of an application or understanding how users are interacting with a system, such as a search engine.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] The syntax and semantics of data within log messages are usually application or vendor-specific.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] The terminology may also vary; for example, the authentication of a user to an application may be described as a log in, a logon, a user connection or an authentication event.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Hence, log analysis must interpret messages within the context of an application, vendor, system or configuration to make useful comparisons to messages from different log sources.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Log message format or content may not always be fully documented.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] A task of the log analyst is to induce the system to emit the full range of messages to understand the complete domain from which the messages must be interpreted.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] A log analyst may map varying terminology from different log sources into a uniform, normalized terminology so that reports and statistics can be derived from a heterogeneous environment.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] For example, log messages from Windows, Unix, network firewalls, and databases may be aggregated into a "normalized" report for the auditor.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Different systems may signal different message priorities with a different vocabulary, such as "error" and "warning" vs.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Hence, log analysis practices exist on the continuum from text retrieval to reverse engineering of software.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Log Analysis is often compared to other analytics tools such as application performance management (APM) and error monitoring.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] While much of their functionality is clear overlap, the difference is rooted in process.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] APM has an emphasis on performance and is utilized most in production.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/log-analysis] Error monitoring is driven by developers versus operations, and integrates into code in exception handling blocks.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] In computing, a **search engine** is an information retrieval software system designed to help find information stored on one or more computer systems.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Search engines discover, crawl, transform, and store information for retrieval and presentation in response to user queries.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The search results are usually presented in a list and are commonly called *hits*.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The most widely used type of search engine is a web search engine, which searches for information on the World Wide Web.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] A search engine normally consists of four components, as follows: a search interface, a crawler (also known as a spider or bot), an indexer, and a database.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The crawler traverses a document collection, deconstructs document text, and assigns surrogates for storage in the search engine index.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Online search engines store images, link data and metadata for the document.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Search engines provide an interface to a group of items that enables users to specify criteria about an item of interest and have the engine find the matching items.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The criteria are referred to as a search query.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] In the case of text search engines, the search query is typically expressed as a set of words that identify the desired concept that one or more documents may contain.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] There are several styles of search query syntax that vary in strictness.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] It can also switch names within the search engines from previous sites.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Whereas some text search engines require users to enter two or three words separated by white space, other search engines may enable users to specify entire documents, pictures, sounds, and various forms of natural language.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Some search engines apply improvements to search queries to increase the likelihood of providing a quality set of items through a process known as query expansion.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Query understanding methods can be used as standardized query language.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The list of items that meet the criteria specified by the query is typically sorted, or ranked.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Ranking items by relevance (from highest to lowest) reduces the time required to find the desired information.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Probabilistic search engines rank items based on measures of similarity (between each item and the query, typically on a scale of 1 to 0, 1 being most similar) and sometimes popularity or authority (see Bibliometrics) or use relevance feedback.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Boolean search engines typically only return items which match exactly without regard to order, although the term *Boolean search engine* may simply refer to the use of Boolean-style syntax (the use of operators AND, OR, NOT, and XOR) in a probabilistic context.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] To provide a set of matching items that are sorted according to some criteria quickly, a search engine will typically collect metadata about the group of items under consideration beforehand through a process referred to as indexing.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The index typically requires a smaller amount of computer storage, which is why some search engines only store the indexed information and not the full content of each item, and instead provide a method of navigating to the items in the search engine result page.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Alternatively, the search engine may store a copy of each item in a cache so that users can see the state of the item at the time it was indexed or for archive purposes or to make repetitive processes work more efficiently and quickly.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Other types of search engines do not store an index.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Crawler, or spider type search engines (a.k.a. real-time search engines) may collect and assess items at the time of the search query, dynamically considering additional items based on the contents of a starting item (known as a seed, or seed URL in the case of an Internet crawler).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Meta search engines store neither an index nor a cache and instead simply reuse the index or results of one or more other search engine to provide an aggregated, final set of results.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Database size, which had been a significant marketing feature through the early 2000s, was similarly displaced by emphasis on relevancy ranking, the methods by which search engines attempt to sort the best results first.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Relevancy ranking first became a major issue c.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] 1996, when it became apparent that it was impractical to review full lists of results.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Consequently, algorithms for relevancy ranking have continuously improved.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Google's PageRank method for ordering the results has received the most press, but all major search engines continually refine their ranking methodologies with a view toward improving the ordering of results.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The sale of search rankings by some search engines has also created controversy among librarians and consumer advocates.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Search engine experience for users continues to be enhanced.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Google's addition of the Google Knowledge Graph has had wider ramifications for the Internet, possibly even limiting certain websites traffic, for example Wikipedia.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] By pulling information and presenting it on Google's page, some argue that it can negatively affect other sites.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] However, there have been no major concerns.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Search engines that are expressly designed for searching web pages, documents, and images were developed to facilitate searching through a large, nebulous blob of unstructured resources.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The process was highly cyclical and continued until enough pages were found for the searcher's use.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] These days, a continuous crawl method is employed as opposed to an incidental discovery based on a seed list.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The crawl method is an extension of aforementioned discovery method.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Most search engines use sophisticated scheduling algorithms to “decide” when to revisit a particular page, to appeal to its relevance.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] These algorithms range from constant visit-interval with higher priority for more frequently changing pages to adaptive visit-interval based on several criteria such as frequency of change, popularity, and overall quality of site.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The speed of the web server running the page as well as resource constraints like amount of hardware or bandwidth also figure in.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Pages that are discovered by web crawls are often distributed and fed into another computer that creates a map of resources uncovered.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The bunchy clustermass looks a little like a graph, on which the different pages are represented as small nodes that are connected by links between the pages.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Another example would be the accessibility/rank of web pages containing information on Mohamed Morsi versus the very best attractions to visit in Cairo after simply entering ‘Egypt’ as a search term.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] One such algorithm, PageRank, proposed by Google founders Larry Page and Sergey Brin, is well known and has attracted a lot of attention because it highlights repeat mundanity of web searches courtesy of students that don't know how to properly research subjects on Google.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The idea of doing link analysis to compute a popularity rank is older than PageRank.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] However, In October 2014, Google’s John Mueller confirmed that Google is not going to be updating it (Page Rank) going forward.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Other variants of the same idea are currently in use – grade schoolers do the same sort of computations in picking kickball teams.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] These ideas can be categorized into three main categories: rank of individual pages and nature of web site content.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Search engines often differentiate between internal links and external links, because web content creators are not strangers to shameless self-promotion.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Link map data structures typically store the anchor text embedded in the links as well, because anchor text can often provide a “very good quality” summary of a web page's content.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Searching for text-based content in databases presents a few special challenges from which a number of specialized search engines flourish.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Databases can be slow when solving complex queries (with multiple logical or string matching arguments).
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Databases allow pseudo-logical queries which full-text searches do not use.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] There is no crawling necessary for a database since the data is already structured.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] However, it is often necessary to index the data in a more economized form to allow a more expeditious search.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Sometimes, data searched contains both database content and web pages or documents.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Search engine technology has developed to respond to both sets of requirements.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Most mixed search engines are large Web search engines, like Google.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] They search both through structured and unstructured data sources.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Take for example, the word ‘ball.’ In its simplest terms, it returns more than 40 variations on Wikipedia alone.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Did you mean a ball, as in the social gathering/dance?
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Pages and documents are crawled and indexed in a separate index.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Databases are indexed also from various sources.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The concept of hypertext and a memory extension originates from an article that was published in *The Atlantic Monthly* in July 1945 written by Vannevar Bush, titled "As We May Think".
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Within this article Vannevar urged scientists to work together to help build a body of knowledge for all mankind.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] He then proposed the idea of a virtually limitless, fast, reliable, extensible, associative memory storage and retrieval system.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Bush regarded the notion of “associative indexing” as his key conceptual contribution.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] As he explained, this was “a provision whereby any item may be caused at will to select immediately and automatically another.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] This is the essential feature of the memex.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The process of tying two items together is the important thing.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] All of the documents used in the memex would be in the form of microfilm copy acquired as such or, in the case of personal records, transformed to microfilm by the machine itself.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Memex would also employ new retrieval techniques based on a new kind of associative indexing the basic idea of which is a provision whereby any item may be caused at will to select immediately and automatically another to create personal "trails" through linked documents.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The new procedures, that Bush anticipated facilitating information storage and retrieval would lead to the development of wholly new forms of the encyclopedia.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The most important mechanism, conceived by Bush, is the associative trail.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] It would be a way to create a new linear sequence of microfilm frames across any arbitrary sequence of microfilm frames by creating a chained sequence of links in the way just described, along with personal comments and side trails.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] In 1965, Bush took part in the project INTREX of MIT, for developing technology for mechanization the processing of information for library use.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] In his 1967 essay titled "Memex Revisited", he pointed out that the development of the digital computer, the transistor, the video, and other similar devices had heightened the feasibility of such mechanization, but costs would delay its achievements.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Gerard Salton, who died on August 28 of 1995, was the father of modern search technology.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] His teams at Harvard and Cornell developed the SMART informational retrieval system.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Salton's Magic Automatic Retriever of Text included important concepts like the vector space model, Inverse Document Frequency (IDF), Term Frequency (TF), term discrimination values, and relevancy feedback mechanisms.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] He authored a 56-page book called *A Theory of Indexing* which explained many of his tests, upon which search is still largely based.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] In 1987, an article was published detailing the development of a character string search engine (SSE) for rapid text retrieval on a double-metal 1.6-μm n-well CMOS solid-state circuit with 217,600 transistors lain out on a 8.62x12.76-mm die area.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The SSE accommodated a novel string-search architecture which combines a 512-stage finite-state automaton (FSA) logic with a content addressable memory (CAM) to achieve an approximate string comparison of 80 million strings per second.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] The CAM cell consisted of four conventional static RAM (SRAM) cells and a read/write circuit.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Concurrent comparison of 64 stored strings with variable length was achieved in 50 ns for an input text stream of 10 million characters/s, permitting performance despite the presence of single character errors in the form of character codes.
[src:aws-opensearch-service/search-engine-computing] Furthermore, the chip allowed nonanchor string search and variable-length `don't care' (VLDC) string search.
